'''Chan Kong-Sang''' ({{zh-stp|s=陈港生|t=陳港生|p=Chén Gǎngshēng}}), also known as '''Sing Lung''' ({{zh-stp|s=成龙|t=成龍|p=Chéng Lóng}}) or '''Jackie Chan''' [[Silver Bauhinia Star|SBS]], (born on [[April 7]], [[1954]]) is a [[China|Chinese]] [[martial artist]], [[actor]], [[Film director|director]], [[screenwriter]], [[film producer]], [[singer]] and [[stunt]] performer.

Chan is one of the best known names in [[kung fu]] and [[action movie]]s worldwide for his [[acrobatics|acrobatic]] [[fighting style]], comic timing, usage of [[improvised weapons]] and for performing many of his own stunts. Having appeared in over a hundred [[film]]s, Chan is one of the most recognisable Asian [[movie star]]s in the world, with stars on the [[Avenue of Stars, Hong Kong|Hong Kong Avenue of Stars]] and the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]. In addition, Chan is an Asian [[cantopop]] star. He has released over 100 song titles on 20 albums since 1984 and sung many of his films' [[Theme music|theme songs]].

==Childhood and beginnings==
[[Image:Young Jackie Chan.jpg|thumb|right|An early photograph of Jackie Chan and his parents.]]
Jackie Chan was born on [[Victoria Peak]], [[Hong Kong]], as Chan Kong-Sang ([[Chinese Language|Chinese]]: 陳港生, meaning "''born in Hong Kong''") and nicknamed "Pao Pao" ([[Chinese Language|Chinese]]: 炮炮, literally meaning "''Cannonball''") because he was always rolling around as an infant.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Biography of Jackie Chan
  | work = Biography
  | publisher = Hong Kong Film.net
  | date =
  | url = http://www.hkfilm.net/chanbio.htm
  | format = 
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-06 }}</ref> His parents [[Charles and Lee-Lee Chan]] were [[refugee]]s from the [[Chinese Civil War]] who worked as a maid and a cook for the [[France|French]] [[Ambassador (diplomacy)|ambassador]] to Hong Kong. Chan spent his formative years within the ambassador's mansion on [[Victoria Peak]] before he and his family emigrated to [[Canberra]], [[Australia]] in 1960.<ref name=Tiscali>{{cite web
  | title = Biography of Jackie Chan
  | work = Biography
  | publisher = Tiscali
  | date =
  | url = http://www.tiscali.co.uk/entertainment/film/biographies/jackie_chan_biog.html
  | format = 
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-06 }}
</ref> As a boy, Chan atteneded Nah-Hwa Primary School, but underperformed. He failed to pass the first grade twice, prompting his father to send him back to Hong Kong, where he was enrolled at the [[Peking Opera School]] run by Master [[Yu Jim Yuen]].<ref name=Tiscali/> 

For the next decade, Chan trained rigourously, excelling at martial arts and acrobatics.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Biography of Jackie Chan
  | work =
  | publisher = StarPulse
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.starpulse.com/Actors/Chan,_Jackie/Biography/
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-06 }}</ref> It was there that Chan would become a member of the [[Seven Little Fortunes]] performance group, the Opera school's best students. A number of these students would ultimately become his Hong Kong film industry compatriots. All attending students took on the family name of their [[sifu]], Chan becoming Yuen Lo. Other attendees included [[Yuen Wah]], [[Corey Yuen]] (Yuen Kwai) and [[Yuen Qiu]]. Chan became close friends with [[Sammo Hung]] (then known as Yuen Lung) and [[Yuen Biao]], and the three of them would later be known as the ''Three Brothers'' / ''Three Dragons''.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Seven Little Fortunes
  | work = Feature article
  | publisher = LoveAsianFilm
  | date =
  | url = http://www.loveasianfilm.com/features/sevenlittlefortunes.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref>

Chan began his career as a stuntman in the [[1971]] [[Bruce Lee]] film ''[[Fist of Fury]]'',<ref name="AskMen">{{cite web
  | title = Men of the Week: Entertainment, Jackie Chan
  | work = Biography 
  | publisher = AskMen
  | date = 
  | url = http://uk.askmen.com/men/entertainment/54c_jackie_chan.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-06 }}</ref> adopting the stage name Chen Yuen Long<ref name="Bioch">{{cite web
  | title = Real Lives: Jackie Chan
  | work = Biography
  | publisher = The Biography Channel
  | url = http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biography_story/861:1217/1/Jackie_Chan.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-06 }}</ref>, which was similar to [[Sammo Hung]]'s Opera School name, to avoid having to put his known name on unsatisfactory films. <ref name="Iamjc">{{cite book
  | last = Chan
  | first = Jackie
  | title = I Am Jackie Chan: My Life in Action
  | publisher = Ballantine Books
  | date = 1999-06-28
  | location =
  | pages =
  | url =
  | doi =
  | isbn = 0-345-42913-3 }}</ref> This included his first starring role at the age of 17, in the 1971 film ''[[Little Tiger of Canton]]'' (aka ''Cub Tiger From Kwang Tung''), which had a limited release in Hong Kong in 1973.<ref name=bioch/>

Chan moved back to Canberra in 1976, attended [[Dickson College]] and briefly and worked on building sites within the [[Australian Capital Territory]].<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = Boogs
  | first = Monika
  | title = Jackie Chan's tears for 'greatest' mother
  | work = 
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher = The Canberra Times
  | date = 2002-03-07
  | url = http://canberra.yourguide.com.au/detail.asp?class=news&subclass=local&story_id=132756&category=general%20news&m=3&y=2002
  | accessdate = 2007-06-06 }}</ref> During his time as a construction worker, a fellow worker named Jack took him under his wing, earning Chan the nickname of "Little Jack" which was later shortened to "Jackie".<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Jackie Chan - Actor and Stuntman
  | work =
  | publisher = BBC
  | date = 2001-07-24
  | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A592760
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-06 }}</ref> Furthermore, Chan's Chinese name was changed in the naming records to "Fong Si Lung" to match his father's original surname - Charles Chan was known as Fong Dao-Long prior to his arrival at Hong Kong.<ref>''I Am Jackie Chan: My Life in Action'', revised paperback edition, p.354, ISBN 0-345-42913-3; [http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117919948?categoryid=31&cs=1&s=h&p=0 Variety Magazine]</ref>

==Acting career==
[[Image:DrunkenMaster DVDcover.jpg|thumb|right|''[[Drunken Master]]'' brought Jackie Chan into the mainstream.]]
===Early exploits: 1976-1980===
Having returned to Hong Kong, Chan joined film director [[Lo Wei]], who planned to model him on Bruce Lee, casting him in the 1976 movie ''[[New Fist of Fury]]''. Chan's stage name was changed to "Shing Lung" ([[Chinese character|Chinese:]] 成龍, literally "become a dragon") to emphasise his similarity to Bruce Lee, whose Chinese name was "Lee Siu Lung" ([[Chinese character|Chinese:]] 李小龍). The film was not a success as Chan's Peking Opera style differed from Bruce Lee's martial arts style. In spite of the film's failure, Lo Wei insisted on producing films with similar themes, resulting in little improvement at the box office.<ref name="FightingMaster">{{cite web
  | title = Jackie Chan, a martial arts success story
  | work = Biography
  | publisher = Fighting Master
  | date =
  | url = http://www.fightingmaster.com/actors/jackie/index.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref>
Between 1976 and 1978, the Lo Wei Motion Picture Company produced several further films featuring Chan, ''[[Shaolin Chamber of Death]]'', ''[[Killer Meteors]]'' (alongside [[Jimmy Wang Yu]]) ''To Kill with Intrigue'' and ''[[Magnificent Bodyguards]]''. During this period, Chan also appeared in smaller roles in several other films, including a supporting role in the [[Golden Harvest]] release, ''[[Hand Of Death]]'', an early film from director [[John Woo]].

Chan's major breakthrough was the 1978 film ''[[Snake in the Eagle's Shadow]]'', directed by [[Yuen Woo Ping]], who granted Chan complete control over his own techniques, hence establishing a new genre of comedic kung fu. The shooting of the film had its dangers, with one of Chan's teeth accidentally kicked out by fellow actor, [[Hwang Jang Lee]]. When released, The movie proved to be a breath of fresh air for the Hong Kong audience and was well received.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Pollard
  | first = Mark
  | title = Snake in the Eagle's Shadow
  | work = Movie review
  | publisher = Kung Fu Cinema
  | date =
  | url = http://www.kungfucinema.com/reviews/snakeintheeaglesshadow.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref> However, it was the 1979 film ''[[Drunken Master]]'' that would propel Chan to mainstream success. The film featured the collaboration between producer [[Ng See Yuen]], [[Yuen Woo Ping]] and fellow members of the Seven Little Fortunes, allowing Chan unlimited creativity over his actions.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Pollard
  | first = Mark
  | title = Drunken Master
  | work = Movie review
  | publisher = Kung Fu Cinema
  | date =
  | url = http://www.kungfucinema.com/reviews/drunkenmaster.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref>

Upon Chan's return to the Low Wei studio, Lo tried to replicate the comedic approach of ''Drunken Master'', producing the films ''[[Spiritual Kung Fu]]'' and ''[[Half a Loaf of Kung Fu]]'' (a film that Lo himself hated.<ref name="Iamjc">{{cite book
  | last = Chan
  | first = Jackie
  | title = I Am Jackie Chan: My Life in Action
  | publisher = Ballantine Books
  | date = 1999-06-28
  | location =
  | pages =
  | url =
  | doi =
  | isbn = 0-345-42913-3 }}</ref>). He also gave Chan the opportunity to co-direct his first film alongside [[Kenneth Tsang]], ''[[Fearless Hyena]]'', which performed well in the box office. The final film Chan completed with Lo's studio was ''[[Dragon Fist]]'' in 1979. During the shooting of ''[[The Fearless Hyena Part II]]'' Chan broke his contract and joined [[Golden Harvest]], prompting [[Lo Wei]] to hire [[triad]]s to blackmail Chan. The dispute was resolved with the help of the actor and director, [[Jimmy Wang Yu]]. Chan was able to stay with Golden Harvest, and directed his second film ''[[The Young Master]]'' in 1980.<ref name="Jcm">{{cite web
  | title = Jackie Chan profile
  | work = Biography
  | publisher = JackieChanMovie.com
  | date =
  | url = http://www.jackiechanmovie.com/profile/biography/bio.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref>

===Success of the comedy kung-fu genre: 1980s===
The 1980s saw Jackie Chan move away from the traditional [[period piece|period]] kung fu films to films set in a more modern era, with more spectacular stunts. The decade also saw Chan's early forays into the [[American film industry]], beginning in 1980, albeit with little success. His first Hollywood movie was ''[[Battle Creek Brawl]]'', directed by [[Robert Clouse]], director of Bruce Lee's ''[[Enter the Dragon]]''. In addition, Chan played a minor role in ''[[The Cannonball Run (film)|The Cannonball Run]]'' (1981), a successful film that grossed [[United States dollar|US$]]100 million worldwide. In spite of being largely ignored in favour of established American actors like [[Burt Reynolds]], Chan was impressed by the [[outtakes]] shown at the closing credits, inspiring him to use the same technique in his future films.<ref name=FightingMaster/> 

After the commercial failure of ''[[The Protector (1985 film)|The Protector]]'', Chan temporarily abandoned his attempts to break into the US market, returning his focus to local films. He began the ''[[Police Story (film)|Police Story]]'' series soon after his return from the United States with the [[Police Story (film)|first film]] released in 1985. The film was a Hong Kong style action-comedy with American influences, and is still considered one of Chan's best films. As in his previous films, all of the dangerous stuntwork was done by Chan himself.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Mills
  | first = Phil
  | title = Police Story (1985)
  | work = Film review
  | publisher = Dragon's Den
  | date =
  | url = http://www.dragonsdenuk.com/reviews/policestory.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref>

Chan married [[Taiwan]]ese actress [[w:zh:林鳳嬌|Lin Feng-Jiao]] ([[Chinese language|Chinese]]: 林鳳嬌) in 1982<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Chan
  | first = Jackie
  | title = Jackie Chan Biography
  | work = Official website of Jackie Chan
  | url = http://www.jackiechan.com/about/about_bio.html
  | accessdate = 2007-06-10 }}</ref> when she got pregnant with their only son,<ref>[http://content.msn.co.in/Entertainment/Bollywood/Bollywood_SantaBanta_050906_1221.htm MSN India on Simi Gatewal's Interview of Jackie Chan], [[5 September]] [[2006]]</ref> [[Jaycee Chan]] (aka Jo-Ming), who was born on December 3, 1982 in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref>{{Citation
  | title = California Birth Index 1905-1995
  | place=California
  | publisher = California Birth index
  | year = 1982-12-03
  | location = Los Angeles County
  | id =  }}</ref>

Between 1983 and 1985, Chan enjoyed his most prolific period of acting alongside his opera school brothers, co-starring with Sammo Hung and Yuen Biao in Chan's ''[[Project A]]'', playing the role of a coastguard in pursuit of a pirate. The film managed to awe and amuse the viewers through its complex stuntwork and choreography, grossing [[Hong Kong dollar|HK$]]19,323,000 and winning the Best Action Choreography Award at the 3rd [[Hong Kong Film Awards]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first = Paul
  | title = Project A Review
  | work = Film review
  | publisher = Hong Kong Cinema
  | date =
  | url = http://www.hkcinema.co.uk/Reviews/projecta.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref> The two years following the success of ''Project A'' were marked by frequent collaboration with Sammo Hung and Yuen Biao, with the three appearing in ''[[Wheels on Meals]]'' and the ''[[Lucky Stars]]'' trilogy between 1983 and 1985. Chan appeared once more with Hung in 1985, in ''[[Heart of Dragon]]''. In 1988, the last film to star all three together, ''[[Dragons Forever]]'', was released.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Sammo Hung Profile
  | work =
  | publisher = Kung Fu Cinema
  | date =
  | url = http://www.kungfucinema.com/people/sammo_hung_kam_bo.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | title = Yuen Biao Profile
  | work =
  | publisher = Kung Fu Cinema
  | date =
  | url = http://www.kungfucinema.com/people/yuen_biao.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref>

===Hollywood Breakthrough: 1990-1998===
[[Image:Rumble In The Bronx.jpg|thumb|right|Chan in his [[Hollywood]] breakthrough film ''[[Rumble in the Bronx]]'']]
In the 1990s, Chan regained his Hollywood ambitions. Early on, he refused two offers to play villains to avoid being [[typecasting (acting)|typecast]] for future roles. When [[Sylvester Stallone]] offered him the role of Simon Phoenix, a criminal in the futuristic film ''[[Demolition Man (film)|Demolition Man]]'', he declined and it was taken by [[Wesley Snipes]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Dickerson
  | first = Jeff
  | title = Black Delights in Demolition Man
  | publisher = The Michigan Daily
  | date = 2002-04-04
  | url = http://media.www.michigandaily.com/media/storage/paper851/news/2002/04/04/TheStatement/Black.Delights.In.demolition.Man-1403498.shtml
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref> He also chose not to play a villain, Wah Sing Su, in the film ''[[Lethal Weapon 4]]'', with the role taken by [[Jet Li]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title =Lethal Weapon 4 Trivia
  | publisher = Internet Movie Database
  | url = http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0122151/trivia
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref>

In 1994, [[MTV]] presented Chan with a lifetime achievement award for his action-oriented movies,<ref name=AskMen/> and a year later, he finally succeeded in capturing the North American market with a worldwide release of ''[[Rumble in the Bronx]]'', attaining the box-office guarantee and [[Cult figure|cult]] popularity that has so far eluded other Hong Kong movie stars like [[Chow Yun-Fat]] and [[Michelle Yeoh]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Morris
  | first = Gary
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors =
  | title = Rumble in the Bronx review
  | work = Film review
  | publisher = Bright Lights Film Journal
  | date = 1996-04
  | url = http://www.brightlightsfilm.com/16/chan.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref> His next success was the [[buddy cop]] action comedy ''[[Rush Hour (film)|Rush Hour]]'' in 1998, co-starring with [[Chris Tucker]],<ref>{{cite web
  | last =
  | first = Raffi
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Rush Hour Review
  | work = Film Review
  | publisher = BeijingWushuTeam.com
  | date = 1998-09-15
  | url = http://www.beijingwushuteam.com/articles/rushhour.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07  }}</ref>, grossing US$130 million in the United States alone.<ref name=Jcm/> Furthermore, he voiced a fictionalized version of himself in a successful [[animated series]], ''[[Jackie Chan Adventures]]''.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Voice actors of Jackie Chan Adventures
  | work = Cast list
  | publisher = VoiceChasers
  | date =
  | url = http://voicechasers.com/database/showprod.php?prodid=233
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref>

[[Image:Jackie Chan star.JPG|thumb|right|Chan's star on the [[Avenue of Stars, Hong Kong|Avenue of Stars]], [[Hong Kong]]]]

===Dramatisation: 1998-present===
In February 1998, Jackie Chan's godfather and co-founder of [[Golden Harvest]], Leonard Ho, died of a stroke.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Filmography of Leonard Ho
  | work =
  | publisher = New York Times
  | date =
  | url = http://movies2.nytimes.com/gst/movies/filmography.html?p_id=182794
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref> Soon afterwards, Chan released his final film for Golden Harvest, ''[[Who Am I?]]'', having been with them for 18 years. Having left Golden Harvest, Chan produced the film ''[[Gorgeous]]'' in 1999, a romantic comedy focusing on personal relationships rather than his fighting abilities.<ref>{{cite video
  | people = Jackie Chan
  | title = Gorgeous, commentary track
  | medium = DVD
  | publisher = Uca Catalogue
  | date = 1999}}</ref> 

In 2003, Chan set up his own film production company [[Jackie Chan Empire Movies Limited]] (JCE) in response to Golden Harvest's departure from the film industry.<ref name=Jcm/> Since then, Jackie Chan's films have featured an increasing number of dramatic scenes as he returned to Hong Kong box office success with [[Benny Chan]]'s ''[[New Police Story]]'' in 2004, playing a troubled police officer,<ref>{{cite web
  | title = New Police Story Review
  | work =
  | publisher = LoveHKFilm
  | date =
  | url = http://www.lovehkfilm.com/reviews_2/new_police_story.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref> ''[[The Myth]]'', playing a modern archaeologist<ref>{{cite web
  | title = The Myth Review
  | work =
  | publisher = Karazen
  | date =
  | url = http://www.karazen.com/reviews/movies/themyth.php
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref> and ''[[Rob-B-Hood]]'', starring as a burglar who kidnaps a baby.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Rob-B-Hood Review
  | work =
  | publisher = HkFlix
  | date =
  | url = http://www.hkcuk.co.uk/reviews/rob_b_hood.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref>
 
Chan continued to garner considerable success in Hollywood with ''[[Shanghai Noon]]'', its sequel ''[[Shanghai Knights]]'', and ''[[Rush Hour 2]]''.<ref name=Jcm/> He also helped to create a [[PlayStation]] game based on him called [[Jackie Chan Stuntmaster]], where he did the voice over and motion capture for the game.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Gerstmann
  | first = Jeff
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title = Jackie Chan Stuntmaster Review
  | work = 
  | publisher = Gamespot
  | date = 2007-01-14
  | url = http://uk.gamespot.com/ps/action/jackiechansstuntmaster/review.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=tabs&tag=tabs;reviews
  | format =
