==Stunts==
[[Image:Jackie Chan Stunt.jpg|thumb|right|Jackie Chan prepares to slide down the side of a building in ''[[New Police Story]]''.]]
Chan is well known for performing the majority of his own stunts, which he choreographs along with his stunt team. In 1983, Chan officially formed the [[Jackie Chan Stunt Team]], allowing him to train and work with a group of trusted martial artists and stuntmen for his subequent films.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Jackie Chan Stuntmen Association Intro
  | work =
  | publisher = HKCinemagic2
  | date = 2002-10
  | language = French
  | url = http://cine-hk.chez-alice.fr/Hkcine/SITE/ARTICLESJ_L/jackie-chan-cascadeurs/JC-stunt-intro.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-06-09 }}</ref> Chan stated that his team makes choreographing easier since he knows the abilities of each individual member. In addition, Chan and his team undertake many of the more dangerous stunts for the other characters, shooting them from behind or otherwise to obscure their faces.<ref name="Newline">{{cite web
  | last = Rogers
  | first = Ian
  | title = Jackie Chan Interview
  | publisher = FilmZone
  | url = http://www.newline.com/jackiechan/Chan/chaninterview.html
  | accessdate = 2007-06-09 }}</ref> 

The dangerous nature of his stunts makes it difficult for Chan to get insurance, especially in the United States, where his stunt work is contractually limited.<ref name=Newline/> Chan holds the [[Guinness World Records|Guinness World Record]] for "Most Stunts By A Living Actor", with the award emphasising that "no insurance company will underwrite Chan's productions, in which he performs all his own stunts".<ref>{{cite web
  | title = January 2003 News Archives
  | work = Jackie Chan Kids
  | date = 2003-01-03
  | url = http://www.jackiechankids.com/files/January_News_Archives.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-06-09 }}</ref> He also holds the record for the most number of takes for a single shot in a film, having shot over 2900 retakes for a complex scene involving a badminton game in ''[[Dragon Lord]]'', although it is not recognized by the Guinness World Records.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Dixon
  | first = Melinda
  | title = Dragon Lord Review
  | work = DVD Bits
  | date = 2006-04-29
  | url = http://www.dvdbits.com/reviews.asp?id=3297
  | accessdate = 2007-06-09 }}</ref> 

Chan has been injured numerous times attempting stunts, with many of those unsuccessful attempts shown during the closing credits of his films. He came closest to death filming ''[[Armour of God]]'' (1985), when he fell from a tree during a relatively routine stunt and fractured his skull, resulting in a permanent hole in his head.<ref>{{Citation
  | last = Chan
  | first = Jackie
  | title = Jackie Chan's Ten Greatest Hits
  | url = http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1FMqo_udPh4
  | accessdate = 2007-06-10 }}</ref> Over the years, Chan has dislocated his [[pelvis]] and broken his [[fingers]], [[toes]], [[nose]], both [[cheekbones]], [[hips]], [[sternum]], [[neck]] and [[ribs]] on numerous occasions.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Chan
  | first = Jackie
  | title = The Official Jackie Chan Injury Map
  | work =
  | publisher = Jackie Chan Kids
  | url = http://www.jackiechankids.com/files/Jackie_Injury_Map_Main.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-06-14 }}</ref>

==Roles played==
{{see|Jackie Chan filmography}}
Jackie Chan originally created his screen persona as a reaction to that of the martial artist [[Bruce Lee]], and the [[Bruceploitation|numerous imitators]] who appeared before and after Lee's death. In contrast to Bruce Lee's characters, who were typically stern, morally upright heroes, Chan plays well-meaning, slightly foolish regular guys often at the mercy of friends, girlfriends or families who always triumph in the end regardless.<ref name=Iamjc/>

In recent years, Chan grew tired of being typecast as an action hero, prompting him to act with more emotions in his latest films. In ''[[New Police Story]]'', he portrayed a character suffering from alcoholism and mourning his murdered colleagues.<ref name="Nps">{{cite video
  | people = Jackie Chan
  | title = New Police Story
  | medium = DVD
  | publisher = JCE Productions
  | location = Hong Kong
  | date = 2004 }}</ref> Age is also a factor, as Chan admitted in an interview with ''[[China Daily]]'' that he could not imagine himself repeating his stunts in ''[[Drunken Master]]''.<ref>{{cite news
  | title = Jackie Chan: From action maestro to serious actor
  | work = China Daily
  | date = 2004-09-24
  | url = http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-09/24/content_377571.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-06-09 }}</ref> In a further attempt to shed the image of Mr. Nice Guy, Chan played an anti-hero for the first time in ''[[Rob-B-Hood]]'' starring as Thongs, a burglar with gambling problems.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = For the first time, Chan plays an unconventional role in his newest comedy (成龙首次尝试反派 联手陈木胜再拍动作喜剧)
  | work = Sina
  | date = 2005-12-30
  | url = http://ent.sina.com.cn/m/c/2005-12-30/0832945759.html
  | language = Simplified Chinese
  | accessdate = 2007-06-09 }}</ref>

== Discography ==
Jackie Chan is a popular and successful [[singer]] in Hong Kong and across Asia, having started professionally producing records in the 1980s. He often sings the theme songs of his own films, playing them at the closing credits.<ref name=Nps/><ref name="Rbb">{{cite video
  | people = Jackie Chan
  | title = Rob-B-Hood
  | medium = DVD
  | publisher = JCE Productions
  | location = Hong Kong
  | date = 2006 }}</ref>
[[Image:Withallonesheart cover.gif|thumb|right|One of Chan's albums, ''With All One's Heart'']]

=== Albums ===
* 1984: ''Love Me''
* 1984: ''Thank You''
* 1985: ''A Boy's Life''
* 1986: ''Shangrila''
* 1986: ''Jackie Chan Sing Lung''
* 1987: ''No Problem''
* 1988: ''Jackie Chan''
* 1992: ''[[First Time (Jackie Chan Album)|First Time]]''
* 1996: ''Dragon's Heart''
* 2002: ''With All One's Heart''

=== Compilation Albums ===
* 1988: ''The Best of Jackie Chan''
* 1988: ''Hong Kong, My Love''
* 1989: ''See You Again''
* 1989: ''Jackie''
* 1990: ''Giant Feelings''
* 1995: ''Best of Movie Themes''
* 1999: ''The Best of Jackie Chan''
* 2000: ''Asian Pop Gold''
* 2005: ''Jackie Chan Greatest Hits''

==Image and celebrity status==
[[Image:HK Star Jackie Chan TST East.jpg|thumb|right|Jackie Chan's fashion shop on the Avenue of Stars, Hong Kong]]
Jackie Chan has received worldwide recognition for his acting, having won several awards including an Innovator Award from the [[American Choreography Awards]] and a [[World Stunt Award]],<ref>{{cite news 
  | title = Jackie Chan From Hong Kong to Receive Stunt Award
  | publisher = Xinhuanet
  | date = 2002-05-16
  | url = http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2002-05/16/content_394957.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-06-11 }}</ref> and has stars on the [[List_of_stars_on_the_Hollywood_Walk_of_Fame#C|Hollywood Walk of Fame]] and the Hong Kong [[Avenue of Stars]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Jackie Chan Picture Page
  | publisher = Superior Pics
  | url = http://www.superiorpics.com/jackie_chan/
  | accessdate = 2007-06-11 }}</ref> Chan has been referenced in various popular media including [[United Kingdom|UK]] band [[Ash (band)|Ash]]'s song [[Kung Fu (song)|''Kung Fu'']], television shows like [[MTV]]'s ''[[Celebrity Deathmatch]]'' and ''[[Family Guy]]''.<ref>{{cite episode
 | title = Masters of the Martial Arts
 | episodelink = 
 | series = Celebrity Deathmatch
 | serieslink = Celebrity Deathmatch
 | airdate = 1999
 | season = 1
 | number = 12 }}</ref><ref>{{cite episode
 | title = Breaking Out Is Hard to Do
 | episodelink = Breaking Out Is Hard to Do
 | series = Family Guy
 | serieslink = Family Guy
 | airdate = 2005-07-17
 | season = 4
 | number = 9}}</ref>He was also the inspiration for manga such as ''[[Dragon Ball]]'',<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Akira Toriyama Interview
  | publisher = Shonen Jump Magazine
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.myfavoritegames.com/dragonball-z/Info/Interviews/Interviews-AkiraToriyama.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-06-27 }}</ref>the character [[Lei Wulong]] in ''[[Tekken]]'' and the fighting-type [[Pokémon]] [[Hitmonchan]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Characters that look like celebrities, etc...
  | publisher = Fighters Generation
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.fightersgeneration.com/funnies/separated/celebs.html
  | accessdate = 2007-06-15 }}</ref> In addition, Chan launched his own line of clothing, which bears a Chinese dragon logo and the English word "Jackie", in 2004.<ref>{{cite news 
  | title = Fashion leap for Jackie Chan as Kung-fu star promotes new clobber
  | work = Agence France Press
  | publisher = JC-News
  | date = 2004-04-02
  | url = http://jc-news.net/news.php?id=316
  | accessdate = 2007-06-15 }}</ref>

Despite having considerable box office success in [[Hollywood]], Chan's American film releases have been criticised due to the action choreography. Reviewers of ''[[Rush Hour 2]]'', ''[[The Tuxedo]]'' and ''[[Shanghai Knights]]'' have criticised the films for toning down Chan's fighting scenes, citing less intensity compared to his earlier films.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Honeycutt
  | first = Kirk
  | title = Rush Hour 2 Review
  | publisher = Hollywood Reporter
  | date = 2001-07-30
  | url = http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=973232
  | accessdate = 2007-06-19 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last = Ebert
  | first = Roger
  | title = The Tuxedo Review
  | publisher = Official website of Roger Ebert
  | date = 2002-09-27
  | url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20020927/REVIEWS/209270305/1023
  | accessdate = 2007-06-19 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last = Pierce
  | first = Nev
  | title = Shanghai Knights Review
  | publisher = BBC film
  | date = 2003-04-03
  | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2003/03/05/shanghai_knights_2003_review.shtml
  | accessdate = 2007-06-19 }}</ref> The comedic value of his films is also questioned, with critics stating that it can be childish at times.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Honeycutt
  | first = Kirk
  | title = Around the World in 80 Days Review
  | publisher = Hollywood Reporter
  | date = 2004-06-16
  | url = http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1000532235
  | accessdate = 2007-06-19 }}</ref>

Chan has always wanted to be a role model to children, being popular with them due to his good natured acting style. He refused offers to play villains and has never used the [[fuck|F-word]] in his films.<ref>{{cite news 
  | title = Jackie Chan Wants to Be Role Model
  | work = The Associated Press
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher = The Advocate
  | date = 2006-08-04
  | url = http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/entertainment/movies/sns-ap-jackie-chan,0,981212.story?coll=sns-ap-movie-headlines
  | accessdate = 2007-06-11 }}</ref> However, he does not mind playing anti-heroes, as seen in ''[[Rob-B-Hood]]''.<ref name=Rbb/> Despite his successful acting career, Chan's greatest regret in life is not having received proper education,<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Webb
  | first = Adam
  | title = Candid Chan: Action star Jackie Chan takes on students' questions
  | publisher = The Flat Hat
  | date = 2000-09-29
  | url = http://flathat.wm.edu/September292000/newsstory2.html
  | accessdate = 2007-06-11 }}</ref> inspiring him to fund educational institutions around the world, including donations to the [[Australian National University]] for the establishment of the Jackie Chan Science Centre,<ref>{{cite press release
  | title = ANU to name science centre after Jackie Chan
  | publisher = Australia National University
  | date = 2006-02-24
  | url = http://info.anu.edu.au/mac/Media/Media_Releases/_2006/_February/_240206jackiechan.asp
  | accessdate = 2007-06-10 }}
</ref> and schools in poor areas of China.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = D
  | first = Mary
  | title = Asian Star Jackie Chan: Worldwide Charitable Entrepreneur
  | publisher = Associated Content
  | date = 2006-12-29
  | url = http://www.associatedcontent.com/article/108663/asian_star_jackie_chan_worldwide_charitable.html
  | accessdate = 2007-06-11 }}</ref>

[[Image:JC Opens Disney HK.jpeg|thumb|Chan with Disney favourites during the opening ceremony of Hong Kong Disneyland]]
Chan is a spokesperson for the [[Government of Hong Kong]], appearing in public service announcements. In a "Clean Hong Kong" commercial, he stated that although people have been saying "Clean Hong Kong" for many years, [[littering]] is still widespread, urging the Hong Kong people to be more considerate.<ref>{{cite video
  | people = Jackie Chan
  | title = Clean Hong Kong
  | medium = Television
  | publisher = Hong Kong Government
  | location = Hong Kong
  | date = 2002 }}</ref> Furthermore, he was featured in an advertisement promoting [[civic engagement|civic awareness]] where he gave a short explanation of the ''[[March of the Volunteers]]'', the national anthem of the [[People's Republic of China]], before it is played.<ref>{{cite news 
  | title = Hong Kong marshal Jackie Chan to Boost Nationalism
  | work = Agencies
  | publisher = China Daily
  | date = 2005-05-18
  | url = http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2005-05/18/content_443738.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-06-11 }}</ref> When [[Hong Kong Disneyland]] opened in 2005, Chan participated in the opening ceremony.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Jackie Chan, Chow Yun-fat among VIPs invited to HK Disneyland opening
  | work = The Associated Press
  | publisher = Sina
  | date = 2005-08-18
  | url = http://english.sina.com/taiwan_hk/1/2005/0818/42863.html
  | accessdate = 2007-06-12 }}</ref> In the United States, Chan has appeared alongside [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] in a government advert to combat [[copyright infringement|piracy]] and has joined forces with Los Angeles County Sheriff [[Lee Baca]] in encouraging people, especially Asians, to join the [[Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department]] in a [[public service announcement]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Schwarzenegger
  | first = Arnold
  | authorlink = Arnold Schwarzenegger
  | coauthors = Jackie Chan
  | title = Anti-piracy advert
  | work = Advertisement
  | publisher = United States Government
  | url = http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=6443035544827856436&q=Jackie+Chan
  | accessdate = 2007-09-10 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last = Park
  | first = Monterey
  | title = Jackie Chan Kicks Off Sheriff's Recruitment Effort
  | work = CBS
  | date = 2007-03-11
  | url = http://cbs2.com/topstories/local_story_070031643.html
  | accessdate = 2007-06-09 }}</ref>

Chan is a keen [[philanthropist]], having worked tirelessly to champion many [[Charitable organization|charity]] works and causes. As a well-respected figure of the Hong Kong entertainment industry and a [[UNICEF]] Goodwill Ambassador, he is often a leader in speaking up for [[Conservation ethic|conservation]], against [[animal abuse]], as well as promoting disaster relief efforts for flooding in [[mainland China]] and the [[2004 Indian Ocean Earthquake|2004 Indian Ocean Tsunami]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Jackie Chan Charity Information
  | publisher = Look to the Stars
  | url = http://www.looktothestars.org/celebrity/80-jackie-chan
  | accessdate = 2007-06-12 }}</ref> In June 2006, he announced that he would donate half of his assets to charity when he dies, stating that he admired the efforts by [[Warren Buffett]] and [[Bill Gates]] to help those in need.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Jackie Chan looks to bequeath half of wealth
  | work = Reuters
  | publisher = The Financial Express
  | date = 2006-06-29
  | url = http://www.financialexpress.com/latest_full_story.php?content_id=132221
  | accessdate = 2007-06-12 }}</ref>

